time required: 40 minutes
cuisine: British
---

Pre-heat your oven to 180 degrees and pop a #pot{} of water on high heat with a
generous pinch of @salt{pinch}. Chop the @purple potato{700%g} into 2cm chunks
(no need to peel) and add to the pot of water. Bring to the boil, then reduce
the heat to medium. Leave your potato to gently bubble away for ~{20%minutes}.

> The potato is cooked when you can easily slip a knife through.

While your potato cooks, get on with the rest of your prep. Remove the root and
dark green parts from the @leek{2}. Slice your leek into circles 1cm thick.
Slice the @spring onion{3} as thinly as you can. Keep to one side.

Pop your #kettle{} on to boil, then dissolve the @chicken stock pot{1/2} in the
@water{150}(boiling). We will use it for your leek later.

Pop a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add @unsalted butter{22.5%g} and all your
leek. Season with a good pinch of @salt{pinch}, a grind of @black pepper{grind}
and cook for ~{3%minutes}, stirring frequently to make sure it doesn't burn. Add
two-thirds of your stock and then transfer your leek and stock to a
#oven-proof dish{} and leave to the side. Wipe the pan clean with #kitchen
paper{}.

Season each @British chicken breasts{2} with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a good
grind of @black pepper{grind}. Heat the same frying pan over high heat and add a
splash of @oil{splash}. Cook your chicken skin-side down for ~{3-5%minutes} or
until the skin is golden and crispy. Turn and cook the flesh side for
~{2%minutes} before transferring your chicken (skin-side up) to the
oven-proof dish{} with your leek. Roast your leek and chicken in your oven for
~{15-17%minutes}.

> The chicken is cooked when the centre is no longer pink.

Keep the pan to one side, we will use it again when your chicken is cooked.

When your potato is cooked, drain into a #colander{} and then return to the
#pot{}. Add your remaining @unsalted butter{22.5%g} and spring onion. Mash
together with a #potato masher{} or #fork{} and then season to taste with @salt
and @pepper. Keep warm with the lid on, we will reheat later.

When your chicken is cooked, remove from your oven and leave to rest for
~{2%minutes}. As your chicken rests, make your glaze. Warm the
@Tracklements rosemary jelly{3} in the frying pan on low heat and add your
remaining chicken stock. Bring to the boil and then remove from the heat.

Reheat your mashed potato over medium heat, stirring continuously until piping
hot. When your potato is hot, spoon a generous amount onto each plate, and serve
your buttered leek alongside (leave any excess liquid behind). Top your leek
with your chicken and spoon your rosemary glaze over your chicken and around
the plate. Enjoy!